Alert HTB

Initial Access

The preliminary Nmap scan just showed two ports open: 22 and 80. As with any box, I first started enumerating the web app, which has a file upload functionality running over Apache and serving PHP files. So, I initiated gobuster scans and more intrusive Nmap scans in the background, and started messing with the web app.

The application required specifically .md files to be uploaded.
So I went ahead with testing any exploits available with a md file exploit and found LFI and XSS. the pure LFI exploit did not work out. And none of my XSS were working properly. Oh, by the way, even though gobuster failed me, feroxbuster found few directories and I also found a subdomain using ffuf.

At this point of time, I was really stuck and took some hints. So, my idea about how to go about this was more or less right, create a XSS mrkdown to get a sensitive file and share the same with Admin via Contact Us page and get some sort of hit back to our server. However, what I couldn't figure out was the payload. Anyway!! First, I went about trying to get the etc/passwd, but no luck.

Then, next thing was to try to get the htaccess file for the statistics subdomain.

And, atlast after multiple machine resets, I got this result. It was a hash which I was able to crack and get the password. Next obvious step, is to try SSHing into the box.

Privilege Escalation

So the next thing was getting root. I noticed there was another user david in the box. Albert didn't have any sudo rights, and the web root folders amounted to nothing. So the next thing I always check are the /opt and /tmp folders, sometimes they contain something interesting, and they did this time. So the Opt folder contains the source for a Website Monitoring app, which alternatively we could have found out by checking the Cron jobs.

So upon notice, we can see we have access to the Monitors folder, which stores the monitoring data. Correspondingly, I checked out the monitor.php file, and noticed that it included something called configuration.php.

So, my thinking was since it "included" as it is, all the contents of the file can potentially execute as root. Moreover, albert belonged to a group "Management" which has write access to the file we want to modify.

Post this, it was simple really, just add a bash reverse-shell one liner and wait for the cron to execute.

And pwned!!
Overall, this was a very informative box, especially getting the Initial access. I faced many problems some from my end, and some due to other errors. Leaving that as it is, I obviously needed help with the payload as I stated earlier, and one of the things that still bugs me is the messages.php endpoint. True, that we got the endpointer while enumerating the directories, but as to how people figured out that it was vulnerable to LFI is something I don't understand really. Got to wait until this box retires I guess.
